{{Aftermath of World War II in Yugoslavia}} '''The Massacre of Gračani''' occurred in May 1945 in Gračani, a neighborhood of [[Zagreb]], [[Croatia]].
After the end of [[World War II]], [[Yugoslav partisans]] and communists started to persecute "national enemies" in Croatia, mostly civilians and captured [[Croatian Armed Forces (Independent State of Croatia)|Croatian]] and [[German Army (Wehrmacht)|German soldiers]]. From May 10, 1945, until July 1945, partisans killed around 6,000 people{{Citation needed|date=October 2018}}. Most of the victims were civilians who didn't agree with the communist regime{{Citation needed|date=October 2018}}. All executions were committed by the 6th Lika Proletarian Division "Nikola Tesla" and members of Yugoslav police (''milicija''){{Citation needed|date=October 2018}}.
All victims were killed in the area of [[Medvednica]]. Later, during investigations in the late 1990s, witnesses described the process of torture and killing. They confirmed that victims were fastened with chains and killed by asphyxiation, shooting or decapitation.<ref>Željko Tomašević, [http://hu-benedikt.hr/?p=5542 ''Hidden graves''], Croatian Association "Benedict", published December 2, 2012, retrieved February 1, 2017 {{hr icon}}</ref> {{Dubious|date=October 2018}}
The first victims were exhumed in October 2012, when forensic experts found and identified 783 bodies in one [[mass grave]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://inavukic.com/2012/10/30/croatia-catholic-church-set-on-ending-distressing-injustice-for-victims-of-communist-crimes/|title=Croatia: Catholic Church set on ending distressing injustice for victims of communist crimes|last=Vukic|first=Ina|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=12 February 2017}}</ref> In another grave, experts found the bodies of 30 teenagers (16–17 years of age) that were bound by chains and appeared to have been shot.<ref>HINA, [http://www.slobodnadalmacija.hr/novosti/hrvatska/clanak/id/183101/zapocelo-otkopavanje-masovnih-grobnica-u-gracanima ''Excavating of mass graves started in Gračani''], [[Slobodna Dalmacija]], published October 22, 2012, access date February 1, 2017 {{hr icon}}</ref>
